[h1]Multiple Backgrounds[/h1]

The ability to have multiple background images is a new feature in CSS3.
Multiple background images are specified using a comma-separated list of values for the background-image property. The first image will appear on the top, the last on the bottom. 

In the example below, we have two background images: the first is a CSS logo (aligned to the bottom and right); the second is a coding image (aligned to the top-left corner). 

[b]The CSS: [/b][code format="css" codeId="614"]div {
  width: 400px;
  height: 300px;
  background-image: [b]url(csslogo.png), url(csscode.jpg);[/b]
  background-position: right bottom, left top;
  background-repeat: no-repeat;
} [/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2703" width="100%"]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to add two background images to the element, with the first positioned at the top left corner, and the other at the top right corner.
[!raw!]
.test {
   background-image: {0}(1.jpg){1} url(2.jpg);
   background-repeat: no-repeat;
   background-position: left {2}, {3} top;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Multiple Backgrounds [/h1]

The position of the background images can be changed, using the background-position property. 
For example: [code format="css" codeId="615"]div {
   width: 400px;
   height: 300px;
   background-image: url(csslogo.png), url(csscode.jpg);
   background-position: [b]right top[/b], left top;
   background-repeat: no-repeat;
} [/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2704" width="100%"]
[note]Multiple backgrounds can also be specified using the [b]background: [/b]shorthand property. [/note]
[code format="css" codeId="616"][b]background:[/b] url(csslogo.png) right top no-repeat, 
url(csscode.jpg) left top no-repeat; [/code]
